===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=狄}}
{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} suggests that the name of the long-tailed pheasant is related to {{och-l|濯|tr=*d-liauk|clean, brilliant, glossy; to moisten, to wash}} and its exopassive {{och-l|濯|tr=*d-liaukh|to wash clothes}} owing to the birds' shiny feathers. See there for further etymology.

STEDT derives this from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-rik ~ *s-rjak||pheasant, partridge}}, for which see {{och-l|雉|pheasant}} for more.

{{zh-ref|Goldin (2011)}} proposes that {{zh-l|翟}} and {{zh-l|狄|northern foreigners}} are related, {{zh-l|狄}} being a "pseudo-ethnonym" meaning "feathered".

